<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-06T23:34:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-06T23:34:00-05:00" n="594" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d594">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/6082: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Harbin</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Jenkins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-07T13:00:00+08:26"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            7, 1920—1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January 7—12:58
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Minister of Finance and several other officials of the Kolchak
                                Cabinet passed Harbin. Indications are that Kolchak Government also
                                thing of the past. Semenoff is issuing orders, appointing generals,
                                creating commissions, and conferring decorations. …</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Jenkins</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>